%N A389255 Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = number of heapable permutations of length n with exactly k decreasing runs.
%C A389255 A permutation of [1..n] is heapable if it can be inserted, one element at a time, into a binary min-heap without violating the heap property.
%C A389255 A decreasing run in a permutation is a maximal contiguous subsequence that is strictly decreasing. For example, in the permutation (3,1,4,2) the decreasing runs are (3,1) and (4,2).
%H A389255 Sean A. Irvine, <a href="/A389255/b389255.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..120</a> (rows 1..15 flattened)
